hshire, Scotland":"Liddisdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Soulle, Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Soules","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Soule  .","French (<b>Soulès</b>): plural form of <b>Soulé</b> (see   Soule  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Soule","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Soul  .","French (<b>Soulé</b>): topographic name for someone who lived in a house exposed to sun, a variant of   Soulier   2; or a habitational name from Soulé, the name of several places in the southwestern part of France.","History: George Soule (1600–80), one of the passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620, was one of the founders of Duxbury, MA, where he became comparatively wealthy. He left eight children."]},{"name":"Sowles","meanings":["English: variant of   Soules  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Soules was born about 1100, in Manche, Normandy, France, his father, Ranulf de Soules, was 22 and his mother, Olive Stebbins, was 19. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. William De Soules. He died before 1170, in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1100–Bef 1170":"umbes 1100–enne 1170","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1120–1164":"1120–1164","1106–Female":"1106–Surnud","1150–1207":"1150–1207","1132–1220":"1132–1220","1080–1170":"1080–1170","1082–1149":"1082–1149","1080":"1080","14 Feb 1149":"14. veebruar 1149","1220":"1220","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1082":"1082","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1149":"1149","Abt 1150":"umbes 1150","Abt 1100":"umbes 1100","1100":"1100","Bef 1170":"enne 1170","1207":"1207","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Liddesdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Liddisdale, Roxburghshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Soulle, Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1100–Bef 1170":"noin 1100–ennen vuotta 1170","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1120–1164":"1120–1164","1106–Female":"1106–Kuollut","1150–1207":"1150–1207","1132–1220":"1132–1220","1080–1170":"1080–1170","1082–1149":"1082–1149","1080":"1080","14 Feb 1149":"14. helmikuuta 1149","1220":"1220","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1082":"1082","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1149":"1149","Abt 1150":"noin 1150","Abt 1100":"noin 1100","1100":"1100","Bef 1170":"ennen vuotta 1170","1207":"1207","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland","Scotla